<br>
I parked the bullet ridden Civic look alike a block away and hobbled to the emergency room entrance. Inside there was a bustle of activity that would have rivaled any airport. I stepped inside. God I hated the smell of hospitals, so clean and sanitary, it made me sick. I thought about just leaving when my leg decided it would remind me of the bullet. So off I went, slowly making my way through a sea of sick and injured people, some of whom had every right to give in and collapse in death. The receptionist looked up at me from her computer screen. She wasn’t that old but, well she wasn’t that womanly either. “Do you need emergency services sir?” She practically barked it. “Well I haven’t got all day, as you can see there are plenty of other patients who need our help as well so spit it out.” <br>
“Uh, well I’ve been shot, in the leg, and it hurts quite a bit, and I was wondering if…” she didn’t let me finish.<br>
“A shooting huh, in the leg you say, doesn’t sound all that urgent. Here fill this form out and wait over there to the left of the room.” She motioned over to the never-ending sea of men, women and children to the left side of the huge room. My face visibly paled. It would take hours, and even though I didn’t know why exactly, I had a feeling I didn’t have hours. I grabbed a space against the wall farthest from the reception desk and closest to the doors leading into the hospital itself. Next to me a homeless man with a nasty looking cut on his head amused himself by talking to a plant. God I hated hospitals. Across the room my eyes locked onto a little kid sitting in her mother’s lap, she had a bottle and she looked content. But her mother looked worried, most likely her husband was inside the emergency room. Suddenly a tall man in a brown suite brushed by her almost knocking the kid out of its mother’s lap. He moved quickly up to the desk, talked with the receptionist for a few seconds, and then she pointed directly at me. Reality hit me like a ton of bricks falling from the Empire State Building, I quickly looked around. The closest exist was into the hospital itself. I looked back over at the man in the suite, he was moving closer. I darted for the door. I didn’t know why it hadn’t occurred to me before, I guess it was because my brain was hazy It made sense that who ever filled my car with bullet holes, and put a bullet in my leg probably wanted to put a bullet in a slightly more debilitating place. I looked around. There was a long white hallway, a water cooler and 2 doors, one said supplies and the other was to far down the hall to read. I needed some relief for my leg, but I also decided that for right now I would need some relief from that man in the suit. The supply door was to close, he would check there first, it seemed my only option was to make my way down the hall. It turned out that the second door was a set of service steps. I pushed the door open and started to stretch my leg. Before my foot hit the ground a shot rang out and the water cooler exploded. I dove into the stair well. Who ever this man was, he sure was anxious to finish the job. I hurled my self down the stairs. My bad leg took this opportunity to have some fun. It decided it would trip me up on one of the turns and send me flying down the stairs head over heals. I heard the door slam, it was followed very quickly by a few more air cracking shots. As I tumbled down the steps paint from the walls, and sparks from the metal stairs flew through the air. God I hated hospitals. I hit the bottom wall, and immediately sprang into a standing position, gritted my teeth as my leg shot a large amount pain up my side and back and then threw myself through the door. Apparently the stairs had led to a sub basement that housed ambulances and repair vans. I decided to take cover behind the closest van. When I was finally stationary behind the rear wheal of the van I had to bite my lip to prevent my mouth from screaming in agony, it seemed that my leg decided it was time to begin worrying about it now. I had to make the difficult realization that I would not be able to run from the man in the brown suit again, so I looked around for a weapon of some kind. As luck would have it, now was the time it decided to repay me for sticking me with the civic, about 5 feet away in the back of a truck lay a large wrench. So large in fact it could only have been used for two things, tightening ludicrously large bolts, or bashing overgrown thugs in brown suits in the head. I tightened my fist around the wrench handle as I heard the door close. I heard the steps of over priced dress shoes coming toward me. Peeking around the corner of the van I saw the man in the suit looking under cars and vans, waving his black hand canon around every time he came up with nothing. I ducked behind the corner when his head started to turn toward me. Well leg, I said to my extremity, don’t fail me now or so help you god I’ll hack you off my self. The man in the suit was about 4 feet away. I turned the corner at a speed I didn’t think was possible raising the wrench above my head as I flew across the floor. For once in my life I had to thank my leg for not following my orders, it collapsed just in time for me to dodge the bullet coming from the muzzle of the gun pointed directly at my face. With all my weight flying forward at a speed that couldn’t have been tracked by radar, I fell to the ground and by another stroke of unbelievable luck the wrench landed heavy end up, right on top of the mans knee. He yelped in pain and dropped to the ground. As if suddenly becoming enlightened he looked up at me as he raised his gun. I took these precious seconds to raise my wrench. Like a bad, low budget action film he leveled his gun, and I allowed gravity to do what it does best. The gun fired, concrete flew into the air, there was a sickening crunching noise, and the wrench bounced off the ground. The man in the brown suit lay crumpled and unconscious in a heap on the ground, his gun still in his hands. I stood up, brushed off my suit, and decided that perhaps it was time to find some painkillers and get the heck out of Dodge. <br>
