d on and showered the room in a faint yellow light. Now picture this, the office was strait out of a Dick Tracey dime novel, files and ash trays covered the floor, filing cabinets overflowing with papers, and an empty bottle of Jim Beam lay on the heavy oak desk. I flicked on the desk lamp, and suddenly the overhead light exploded in a cascade of sparks, apparently this guy hadn’t invested in high end light fixtures. On the desk lay a file with a picture of a knock out blonde. Her name was Angelica Keys. Apparently this P.I. had been tailing her or something. Next to the folder lay a key ring with 2 small keys on them, I guessed they belonged to the safe in the corner. I picked them up and limped over to the safe, I inserted one and then the other. After turning them I was rewarded with a solid sound of a heavy locking mechanism sliding out of place. Inside lay a pile of cash, another bottle of whiskey and a few clips but no gun. I stood up and walked back over to the desk and sat down. This guy was a slob, but he had style. I took another drag of my cigarette and leafed through the file of the lady with the great smile. She was 27, and enjoyed dancing and the night club scene. Her father was a wealthy real-estate tycoon, who decided it was time he found out what his lovely young daughter was up to. I poured myself a large glass of Jim Beam ignoring all the advice I had heard in school about not mixing sedatives and alcohol. I sat back sighing stretching my leg out. The hospital goodies had completely numbed it not to mention the rest of my body, and for the first time in a few hours I felt almost good. I stared at the picture of the lady and watched it slowly dance around on the manila folder. I drank the last of the whiskey and stood up. Just before I collapsed I saw a picture on the filing cabinet behind the desk. The face looked very familiar, very familiar. Oh well I though, then the world turned black. <br>
