<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It was about lunchtime when we reached the diner/ pastry shop on Belmont Ave. Inside it smelled like a mix of coffee, doughnuts and eggs. There were about 13 people in the building including a waitress and the chef. Angel and I decided on a booth near the back and ordered some of the coffee that was wafting through the air. I light a cigarette and looked over the beauty sitting across from me. She was just like in her file picture only more stunning, long blond hair, slim face and body and nice legs. “So what happened Jackson?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No idea. All I know is I woke up in a run down parking garage with a bullet in my leg and a bad hangover.” She didn’t look surprised. “I have faint memories of what happened but nothing really concrete or conclusive. Say what did you ask me earlier about your fathers plans?” <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I asked if you had any new leads, you were supposed to meet me at Club Beau at 12:30 but you never showed. You said you had some news you wanted to share. Something about the buildings on 12th street my father had just acquired.” I took a sip of coffee and mulled it over in my head. According to the file her father owned just about 14% of the entire city of New York, that included all the suburbs. The coffee was warm but that was its only attribute. “So you really don’t remember anything before you woke up in that garage?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No not a thing, until you showed up this morning and put that gun to my face I still hadn’t known my own name. Well I had an idea but, well it wasn’t a solid lead if you know what I’m saying.” I took a large sip of the brown stuff in the cup supposably called coffee and then another drag from my cigarette. “I remember you father though, tall fat guy with an expensive suit, and walks with a cane, right?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yeah that’s him, he always said he liked to dress like a tycoon, said it made him feel powerful. I think he just looked old.” She lifted her cup and took a sip. My eyes moved over the room slowly, contemplating the information I had been given. There was an old couple sitting about 3 booths from us, the lady had hair that had a tint of blue. And the old guy was smoking a pipe. The only thing worse than hospitals was the thought of growing old. “That’s crazy, it’s like right out of a novel or something.” Angel was talking about my amnesia again, but I had slipped into another world with thoughts flying all over the place, wild speculations and theories of what had happened a night ago. Suddenly I snapped back into reality as the second ton of high velocity bricks in the past day slammed into my head. There was a cop, big fat, brown hair, and a scared pocked face standing in the door. I had a vision of him standing next to a man in a gray overcoat laughing. He looked over at me and paled. “What is it Jackson” asked Angel, she turned and saw the large cop heading toward us. “Oh no, its Max, one of my dads friends.” Another vision exploded before my eyes of Max’s monstrous hand falling down on me. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “We’ll hello there friend” Max bellowed as he sat down next to Angel sneering at me, “I’m glad to see your upright and moving.” I fingered my .45 under my coat, but decided I was only going to use it if absolutely necessary. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Nice to see you as well Max” I said almost spitting when I said the name. “I’m sure you slept well last night.” That fat bastard almost laughed. “Of course, but not as well as you I’d say.” I ran through my mind the thought of pulling the piece and putting a hole in his forehead, but after looking around and seeing all the witnesses I decided against it. “How’s the leg?” Max said, once again sneering. An image of a man in a brown suit appeared before me holding his hand canon. I saw a flash of light, and heard an explosion, in the background stood a man in a gray overcoat and a fat police officer.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A cold sweat had formed on my brow, “Is there a problem, friend?” asked Max in an evil tone. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No, no, none at all. Lets go Angel.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No stay enjoy your breakfast Jackson,” said Max, “I suggest the eggs, they aren’t fresh, may not even be eggs but there better than the coffee.” And with that Max the fat ugly cop got up and left. I hated cops too, but the coffee was worse.<br>
<br>
