<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp We flew down the freeway in the bright red Mazda at speeds of almost 80 mph. The sun had hidden itself behind a thick covering of clouds and it was beginning to rain. Aside from the knowledge that Max the overweight cop and the thug in the brown suit were working together, I had nothing. Supposedly Angels father had some plan for some property he had just bought, and my guess was that the plans were big. Big enough for him to send three goons to make sure I didn’t ever tell anyone what those plans were. So far I’d have to say he was doing a pretty good job. I mauled over the images I had seen in my brain for what seemed like ages. The man in the brown suit firing his gun, Max beating me to a pulp and that man in the gray over coat who’s face I couldn’t see who was laughing the whole time. It was like being trapped in a prison with no walls but still no sunlight or a way out. I lit another cigarette. The painkillers had started to ware off and I was becoming a little irritated. “So where are we going then Angel dear?” I asked snidely. &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Calm down Jackson and take some painkillers, we’re going to see my father’s empire up close, perhaps that will jog your memory.” And so on we drove into an ever-increasing rain, it was strangely fitting somehow. By the time I had started on my second cigarette we had made it to 12th Street. Standing before us stood 6 large sky scrappers with scaffolding sticking out the sides. “So this is it, in all its glory, a 10,000,000,000 dollar square block. If I didn’t resent him so much I might even be impressed.” She said it with what might have been mistaken for respect. I puffed on the cigarette enjoying the numbness of the painkillers, it really was an impressive sight. “So this doesn’t jog your memory at all? Not even a little?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Afraid not Angel, maybe we should take a look around.” We walked across the street and into the lobby of one of the buildings. It had a huge stone almost gothic look to it. Stone statues of angels and gargoyles covered the walls. “You’re dad have a thing for religion?” I asked, partly because the figures freaked me out and partly because I figured anything right now was better than nothing.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “No, he just likes the way it makes the lobby look, at least that’s the way I figure it.” We looked around slowly, examining everything. After searching the whole ground floor of this newly acquired building we decided that maybe we should see what was up farther. We stopped the service elevator at the 12 floor. This floor still had white painters sheets covering the floor and walls, buckets of white and brown paint lying about and surprisingly no workers. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Looks as if they’re on break” I said, looking around “nobody’s around” I was right not a single soul inhabited this floor, not a painter, not even a Foreman. I brushed it off as the painkillers making me paranoid. Well this floor sure isn’t bringing back any memories, good or bad. I stepped to a big floor to ceiling window and looked down, people were going in and out of all the buildings, except this one. In fact the only activity I saw coming from this building was a group of 7 men leaving, in a hurry. A thought began to cross my mind but before I could finish, a long silver and black Rolls Royce pulled up and from the back door stepped a man in a gray overcoat.<br>
<br>
